and she told her secretary
to tell him

964
00:50:28,320 --> 00:50:30,160
that she not only
didn't want a gofer,

965
00:50:30,230 --> 00:50:31,780
she didn't want
a cheeseburger, either.

966
00:50:31,860 --> 00:50:34,560
And that she was going
to get a sandwich
over at Tony's.

967
00:50:34,630 --> 00:50:37,220
And she said to tell
her husband the same thing.

968
00:50:37,300 --> 00:50:38,430
I see.

969
00:50:38,500 --> 00:50:40,160
Well, no you don't, sir.

970
00:50:40,240 --> 00:50:42,230
I mean, you must
have seen before.

971
00:50:43,010 --> 00:50:45,000
Because you were
in the room

972
00:50:45,070 --> 00:50:46,630
when she took the call,
werert you?

973
00:50:47,680 --> 00:50:50,200
She made it from
this dressing room.

974
00:50:51,110 --> 00:50:53,050
I don't know.
I'm not sure.

975
00:50:54,420 --> 00:50:57,250
I'm not in the habit
of listening to other people's
telephone calls.

976
00:50:59,760 --> 00:51:03,380
I didn't know that Claire
was going to Tony's.

977
00:51:03,460 --> 00:51:04,450
You didn't, sir?

978
00:51:04,560 --> 00:51:06,320
Absolutely not,
Lieutenant.

979
00:51:06,400 --> 00:51:09,850
Then how did you know,
sir, that there were
only four people

980
00:51:09,930 --> 00:51:12,260
who knew where Claire Daley
was going to be that night

981
00:51:12,340 --> 00:51:14,740
and how did you know
that you were one of them?

982
00:51:15,740 --> 00:51:17,000
The same way
you did.

983
00:51:17,070 --> 00:51:18,940
I asked Claire's secretary
and she informed me

984
00:51:19,010 --> 00:51:20,500
that the call was made
from my room.

985
00:51:20,780 --> 00:51:22,070
You did, sir?

986
00:51:22,580 --> 00:51:24,340
Oh, yes, I did,
Lieutenant.

987
00:51:24,810 --> 00:51:27,150
Oh, that's
very good, sir.

988
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:31,610
Thank you, Lieutenant.
I believe you meant that.

989
00:51:32,660 --> 00:51:34,120
Oh, I did, sir.

990
00:51:36,390 --> 00:51:38,590
I'd say we make rather
a good team, don't you?

991
00:51:38,760 --> 00:51:41,060
Yeah. Sort of like
Sherlock Holmes
and Watson, sir.

992
00:51:41,130 --> 00:51:42,760
No, no, no,
no, no.

993
00:51:42,830 --> 00:51:47,170
More like Sherlock Holmes
and Sherlock Holmes.

994
00:51:47,300 --> 00:51:49,100
Well, what I mean, sir,
is the way I see it,

995
00:51:49,170 --> 00:51:51,370
I'm working with
the highest paid detective
in the world.

996
00:51:52,070 --> 00:51:53,700
It's not as high
as it sounds.

997
00:51:53,780 --> 00:51:55,970
Not when you have to pay out
as much as I do.

998
00:51:56,150 --> 00:51:58,770
Well, I gotta get
to work on Sid Daley.

999
00:51:59,620 --> 00:52:01,950
Boy, it's hard to find
someone in Rome, sir.

1000
00:52:02,020 --> 00:52:03,420
Yes, I imagine.

1001
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:07,220
But his story has
to be checked out
just like anybody else's.

1002
00:52:07,420 --> 00:52:09,220
Oh, by the way,
sir,

1003
00:52:09,890 --> 00:52:12,590
did I mention
that we found the gun
in the prop department?

1004
00:52:12,900 --> 00:52:16,630
No. What you said was
that was where you were
gonna look for one.

1005
00:52:16,700 --> 00:52:18,930
Oh, that's right, sir.
Right.

1006
00:52:19,740 --> 00:52:22,000
And you didn't wanna
jump to conclusions.

1007
00:52:22,140 --> 00:52:23,730
No good detective
should.

1008
00:52:24,270 --> 00:52:25,900
Was there anything
on the gun?

1009
00:52:30,210 --> 00:52:31,980
Anything like
what, sir?

1010
00:52:33,680 --> 00:52:35,010
Fingerprints,
what else?

1011
00:52:35,080 --> 00:52:37,880
Oh, right.
No, I don't think so, sir.

1012
00:52:38,420 --> 00:52:41,020
The lab is
still running tests.

1013
00:52:42,560 --> 00:52:44,420
By the way, sir,

1014
00:52:44,560 --> 00:52:46,190
why do you think
he put the gun back

1015
00:52:46,260 --> 00:52:48,060
and threw away
everything else?

1016
00:52:50,430 --> 00:52:52,870
Perhaps because
he didn't have time
to get rid of the gun safely.

1017
00:52:53,300 --> 00:52:55,100
Guns are very easy
to trace.

1018
00:52:55,300 --> 00:52:56,400
And the prop room

1019
00:52:56,470 --> 00:52:58,300
may have seemed
the safest place to him.

1020
00:53:00,840 --> 00:53:02,000
I think
you hit it again, sir.

1021
00:53:02,080 --> 00:53:03,100
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

1022
00:53:03,180 --> 00:53:04,580
ASSISTANT DIRECTOR:
Ready when you are,
Mr. Fowler.

1023
00:53:04,650 --> 00:53:05,670
Be right there.

1024
00:53:05,750 --> 00:53:07,770
Oh, sir, if you didn't think
I was gonna be in the way,

1025
00:53:07,850 --> 00:53:08,840
I would love to...

1026
00:53:08,920 --> 00:53:10,150
No. Not at all.
Be my guest.

1027
00:53:10,220 --> 00:53:12,280
Oh, thank you very much,
sir. I appreciate that.

1028
00:53:12,720 --> 00:53:15,420
Excuse me, sir.

1029
00:53:16,030 --> 00:53:18,150
I don't wanna
appear grabby,

1030
00:53:19,230 --> 00:53:21,090
but do you think I could
have one of these, sir?

1031
00:53:22,400 --> 00:53:23,990
Certainly.
As many as you want.

1032
00:53:24,070 --> 00:53:25,620
That's the usual
publicity nonsense.

1033
00:53:25,700 --> 00:53:27,600
Ward Fowler this,
Ward Fowler that.
Nothing.

1034
00:53:27,900 --> 00:53:30,530
Nothing to you sir,
but to my wife...

1035
00:53:31,040 --> 00:53:33,100
Boy, she's gonna
be tickled pink.

1036
00:53:38,150 --> 00:53:39,170
(CLEARS THROAT)

1037
00:53:39,250 --> 00:53:41,050
But blend it on.
All right.

1038
00:53:41,120 --> 00:53:43,920
No. I mean blend it,
especially on this side.

1039
00:53:44,150 --> 00:53:46,780
Oh, I see.
All right.

1040
00:53:47,490 --> 00:53:48,680
Like that?

1041
00:53:48,760 --> 00:53:50,490
I can't tell.

1042
00:53:51,460 --> 00:53:53,760
Oh, am I in the way, sir?
Oh, forgive me.
I didn't mean to intrude,

1043
00:53:53,830 --> 00:53:55,590
That's all right,
Lieutenant.

1044
00:53:55,660 --> 00:53:56,690
That's remarkable.

1045
00:53:56,770 --> 00:53:57,890
Yes, sir.

1046
00:53:57,970 --> 00:53:59,300
Remarkable
how you do that, sir.

1047
00:53:59,370 --> 00:54:00,670
My wife would like
to have you around.

1048
00:54:00,740 --> 00:54:02,100
Thank you, Lieutenant.

1049
00:54:02,170 --> 00:54:04,800
You know, this bio, sir,

1050
00:54:04,870 --> 00:54:06,710
it doesn't say
anything about

1051
00:54:06,780 --> 00:54:09,010
when you were
first discovered,

1052
00:54:09,110 --> 00:54:10,910
and what you were doing
when you were discovered,

1053
00:54:10,980 --> 00:54:12,210
who discovered you.

1054
00:54:12,280 --> 00:54:13,310
I'm going to have
a little chat

1055
00:54:13,380 --> 00:54:14,910
with the publicity department
about that.

1056
00:54:15,020 --> 00:54:17,250
Come to
think of it, sir,

1057
00:54:17,320 --> 00:54:19,050
it was Mrs. Daley
who discovered you, wasrt it?

1058
00:54:19,120 --> 00:54:22,350
Now, Lieutenant,
I told you all about that
with great emotion

1059
00:54:22,430 --> 00:54:24,760
and in great detail
the first time we met.

1060
00:54:24,830 --> 00:54:26,990
Well, that's what I mean, sir,
it should be in here.

1061
00:54:27,060 --> 00:54:28,390
Excuse me, Kenny.
Thank you.

1062
00:54:28,460 --> 00:54:29,800
Where were you
and when...

1063
00:54:32,740 --> 00:54:35,100
Lieutenant, why don't you
just ask me

1064
00:54:35,170 --> 00:54:36,640
what it is
you wanna know?

1065
00:54:36,710 --> 00:54:39,140
Where did Mrs. Daley
discover you, sir?

1066
00:54:39,210 --> 00:54:41,180
That's something even
my wife doesn't know.

1067
00:54:41,240 --> 00:54:43,610
It doesn't say anything
here in the bio.

1068
00:54:43,750 --> 00:54:46,840
It doesn't even say
whether Ward Fowler's
your real name or not.

1069
00:54:46,920 --> 00:54:50,010
And that's something
any <i>Lieutenant Lucerne</i> fan
would wanna know.

1070
00:54:50,090 --> 00:54:51,280
Why don't we
stop pretending

1071
00:54:51,350 --> 00:54:53,080
that I'm brilliant and you're
simple for one moment.

1072
00:54:53,190 --> 00:54:54,660
I'm gonna confide
something in you.

1073
00:54:54,720 --> 00:54:58,280
Anything you tell me, sir,
it's between us.
Like the shoes.

1074
00:54:58,690 --> 00:55:01,160
Lieutenant,
my real name,

1075
00:55:01,660 --> 00:55:03,830
so help me,
Charles Kipling.

1076
00:55:03,900 --> 00:55:05,230
And you're the only one
who knows that.

1077
00:55:05,300 --> 00:55:07,700
Now, Charles Kipling was
in a little bit of trouble

1078
00:55:07,770 --> 00:55:08,830
when Claire
first found him.

1079
00:55:08,900 --> 00:55:11,840
Actually, I was
doing theater
in Toronto.

1080
00:55:12,170 --> 00:55:14,570
Claire and I hit it off big,
she thought I had
a great future,

1081
00:55:14,640 --> 00:55:16,540
she persuaded me
to leave Canada.

1082
00:55:16,610 --> 00:55:18,080
And that was
the beginning.

1083
00:55:18,150 --> 00:55:21,380
The trouble straightened
itself out, of course.

1084
00:55:21,580 --> 00:55:24,050
But I've always been
a little sensitive about it.

1085
00:55:24,120 --> 00:55:25,110
You understand?

1086
00:55:25,220 --> 00:55:27,190
Oh, I certainly do,
sir.

1087
00:55:29,290 --> 00:55:32,450
Lou, Lou, I'm talking,
but you're not listening.

1088
00:55:33,230 --> 00:55:35,290
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)
There's no money
in the budget.

1089
00:55:37,100 --> 00:55:39,690
Lou, will you believe me?
There's no money.

1090
00:55:44,140 --> 00:55:47,340
Look, that's the way it is,
take it or leave it.

1091
00:55:49,550 --> 00:55:52,140
Good. Good.
You got yourself a deal.

1092
00:55:53,280 --> 00:55:54,680
What is it this time,
Lieutenant?

1093
00:55:54,750 --> 00:55:56,380
I'm a very busy man.

1094
00:55:56,590 --> 00:55:59,650
There was no one
out there, sir.

1095
00:55:59,720 --> 00:56:00,750
It's all right.

1096
00:56:00,820 --> 00:56:02,550
So I just came in.
Congratulations.

1097
00:56:02,860 --> 00:56:04,290
Congratulations
for what?

1098
00:56:04,360 --> 00:56:06,390
I heard you came into
a lot of money.

1099
00:56:06,460 --> 00:56:09,660
I see. You heard
about my little windfall?

1100
00:56:09,870 --> 00:56:11,030
Yes, sir, I have.

1101
00:56:11,100 --> 00:56:13,500
Lieutenant, if you think
I knew anything about this,

1102
00:56:13,570 --> 00:56:14,900
you're wrong.

1103
00:56:15,270 --> 00:56:16,570
My lawyer called me
and told me

1104
00:56:16,640 --> 00:56:18,110
my wife's safe deposit box

1105
00:56:18,170 --> 00:56:20,230
was practically layered

1106
00:56:20,310 --> 00:56:22,570
with receipts for these
silver certificates.

1107
00:56:23,110 --> 00:56:25,600
I'll be damned
if I can figure out
how she did it.

1108
00:56:25,680 --> 00:56:27,710
I think the government's gonna
have a little trouble, too,

1109
00:56:27,780 --> 00:56:29,680
because she never
declared them as income.

1110
00:56:29,750 --> 00:56:34,020
She kept the certificates
in a numbered account
in a Canadian bank.

1111
00:56:34,360 --> 00:56:36,050
And it all goes to you,
right, sir?

1112
00:56:36,390 --> 00:56:39,590
And it all goes to me.
After taxes.

1113
00:56:39,760 --> 00:56:44,130
Including a few lovely IOUs
from Ward Fowler.

1114
00:56:44,330 --> 00:56:47,430
Is that so, sir?
That's surprising, isn't it?

1115
00:56:47,500 --> 00:56:48,970
Considering all the money
he makes.

1116
00:56:49,040 --> 00:56:51,440
I never question good fortune,
Lieutenant.

1117
00:56:51,640 --> 00:56:54,340
All I know is that
getting along
with Ward Fowler

1118
00:56:54,410 --> 00:56:55,970
is gonna be
a lot easier from now on.

1119
00:56:56,050 --> 00:56:57,640
What about a drink?

1120
00:56:57,780 --> 00:56:59,940
That's amazing
how she kept it from you.

1121
00:57:00,020 --> 00:57:02,580
Well she did.
I just found out about it.

1122
00:57:02,650 --> 00:57:05,520
Yes, sir, I know.
Your accountant told me.

1123
00:57:06,160 --> 00:57:08,350
Oh. Well, good.

1124
00:57:08,560 --> 00:57:09,820
Then that's it, huh?

1125
00:57:09,890 --> 00:57:11,190
Yes, sir, that's it.

1126
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:16,330
Oh, there's
one more thing, sir.

1127
00:57:17,930 --> 00:57:19,660
Mr. Hart
is in Rome.

1128
00:57:19,740 --> 00:57:22,400
He's gonna be back
in his hotel room
in a little while.

1129
00:57:22,810 --> 00:57:24,770
Before I talk to him,

1130
00:57:26,540 --> 00:57:29,070
were you really playing chess
the other night?

1131
00:57:31,510 --> 00:57:33,670
Lieutenant, let's get it
straight right now.

1132
00:57:34,180 --> 00:57:36,580
I was not with Leo Hart
the other night.

1133
00:57:38,350 --> 00:57:40,520
But I wasrt busy
killing my wife, either.

1134
00:57:41,820 --> 00:57:42,810
(BUZZER SOUNDING)

1135
00:57:46,100 --> 00:57:47,560
Yes, Mr. Daley?

1136
00:57:47,630 --> 00:57:50,330
SID: Molly, would you
come in for a minute?
I need your help.

1137
00:57:53,870 --> 00:57:55,890
Molly, would you please
tell Lieutenant Columbo

1138
00:57:55,970 --> 00:57:57,460
where I was
on Thursday evening,

1139
00:57:57,610 --> 00:57:59,300
the night
my wife was killed?

1140
00:57:59,380 --> 00:58:00,360
The truth.

1141
00:58:01,940 --> 00:58:04,380
Mr. Daley was with me,
Lieutenant.

1142
00:58:04,780 --> 00:58:06,610
We left the office
together

1143
00:58:07,050 --> 00:58:08,410
and we were together

1144
00:58:08,920 --> 00:58:11,150
in my apartment
until the next morning.

1145
00:58:11,290 --> 00:58:12,720
It's the truth.

1146
00:58:12,820 --> 00:58:14,290
Yes, madam.

1147
00:58:14,420 --> 00:58:16,220
I believe it is.

1148
00:58:21,300 --> 00:58:23,030
Good afternoon,
Lieutenant Lucerne.

1149
00:58:23,700 --> 00:58:26,690
I suppose you came here
for a confession.

1150
00:58:26,770 --> 00:58:28,830
Well, you're not
going to get it, sir.

1151
00:58:28,900 --> 00:58:29,890
(LAUGHING)

1152
00:58:30,040 --> 00:58:32,940
Because

1153
00:58:33,010 --> 00:58:35,270
you don't have
the facts, sir.

1154
00:58:35,340 --> 00:58:36,540
(CHUCKLING)

1155
00:58:36,750 --> 00:58:39,110
Wait a minute.
You're gonna love it.

1156
00:58:39,180 --> 00:58:40,710
Let's see
what we got here.

1157
00:58:42,990 --> 00:58:43,970
All right.

1158
00:58:48,020 --> 00:58:50,150
I don't know why
you started laughing.

1159
00:58:50,390 --> 00:58:51,480
Here.

1160
00:58:57,700 --> 00:58:59,070
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

1161
00:59:00,670 --> 00:59:02,730
<i>Good afternoon,</i>
<i>Lieutenant Lucerne.</i>

1162
00:59:03,540 --> 00:59:06,370
<i>I suppose you came here</i>
<i>for a confession.</i>

1163
00:59:06,680 --> 00:59:08,470
<i>Well, you're not</i>
<i>going to get it, sir.</i>

1164
00:59:08,540 --> 00:59:09,530
<i>(WARD LAUGHING)</i>

1165
00:59:11,180 --> 00:59:15,910
I'm just silly, sir,
but that machine,
that is really fantastic.

1166
00:59:17,350 --> 00:59:21,760
How much, roughly,
would a thing like that cost?

1167
00:59:21,860 --> 00:59:25,160
Oh, about $3,000.
Not counting the camera,
of course.

1168
00:59:25,690 --> 00:59:27,630
Three thousand?
Dollars?

1169
00:59:28,530 --> 00:59:31,590
Why, I can get a new car
for that. Not that I need one.

1170
00:59:31,830 --> 00:59:33,200
Lieutenant,

1171
00:59:35,170 --> 00:59:37,260
you have something
to say to me, don't you?

1172
00:59:37,610 --> 00:59:41,060
Yes, sir. I'm really sorry
to bother you like this, sir.

1173
00:59:41,140 --> 00:59:45,050
But just a couple of questions
before my report on Sid Daley.

1174
00:59:45,110 --> 00:59:47,140
It doesn't look like
he could have done it, sir.

1175
00:59:47,220 --> 00:59:49,150
He was with a girl
and she confirmed it.

1176
00:59:49,220 --> 00:59:50,780
I see.

1177
00:59:52,860 --> 00:59:53,840
I tell you what.

1178
00:59:54,920 --> 00:59:57,890
Let's you and I discuss
what I have to tell you first.

1179
00:59:58,730 --> 01:00:02,190
And then we can both
interrogate Ward Fowler.

1180
01:00:02,300 --> 01:00:03,590
You see,
as Lieutenant Lucerne,

1181
01:00:03,670 --> 01:00:06,500
I have a rather unpleasant
idea taking shape in my mind.

1182
01:00:06,700 --> 01:00:07,830
Brandy?

1183
01:00:08,170 --> 01:00:09,160
Thank you, sir.

1184
01:00:09,740 --> 01:00:11,260
What might that be, sir?

1185
01:00:11,370 --> 01:00:14,310
Well, that might be...
And I'm speaking strictly
as Lucerne, of course.

1186
01:00:14,380 --> 01:00:15,370
Of course.

1187
01:00:16,550 --> 01:00:19,910
It just might be,
unlikely as it may seem,

1188
01:00:20,350 --> 01:00:24,080
it just might
conceivably be

1189
01:00:25,650 --> 01:00:28,150
Ward Fowler
is the man we're after.

1190
01:00:28,760 --> 01:00:30,280
You mean the murderer?

1191
01:00:30,360 --> 01:00:31,450
Exactly.

1192
01:00:32,960 --> 01:00:33,950
No.

1193
01:00:34,530 --> 01:00:37,930
Yes. I know this comes
as a shock to you.

1194
01:00:40,070 --> 01:00:41,970
But let's think about it.

1195
01:00:43,270 --> 01:00:45,570
Let's examine
the possibilities.

1196
01:00:45,640 --> 01:00:48,870
Well, if you say so, sir,

1197
01:00:49,380 --> 01:00:52,680
but I don't see
where there could be
possibly a motive.

1198
01:00:53,050 --> 01:00:56,110
Why would Ward Fowler
wanna kill Claire Daley?

1199
01:00:56,190 --> 01:00:57,850
It's Claire Daley
who made him famous.

1200
01:00:57,920 --> 01:00:59,580
That's what I
was wondering and then

1201
01:00:59,660 --> 01:01:02,280
I got to thinking
about the IOUs.

1202
01:01:03,530 --> 01:01:04,720
Oh, did you, sir?

1203
01:01:04,790 --> 01:01:06,420
Yes. Oddly enough I did.

1204
01:01:06,530 --> 01:01:08,500
I'm speaking as Lucerne,
of course.

1205
01:01:08,730 --> 01:01:10,360
Yes, of course.

1206
01:01:11,330 --> 01:01:14,300
Half a million dollars
in IOUs. Wow!

1207
01:01:15,840 --> 01:01:18,600
I couldn't help wondering why,
with all the money

1208
01:01:19,810 --> 01:01:21,240
that Ward Fowler makes,

1209
01:01:21,310 --> 01:01:23,540
he could owe
Claire Daley that much.

1210
01:01:24,580 --> 01:01:26,010
And then it hit me.

1211
01:01:26,250 --> 01:01:27,840
What hit you, sir?

1212
01:01:29,250 --> 01:01:30,240
Coffee?

1213
01:01:30,990 --> 01:01:32,010
Thank you.

1214
01:01:32,860 --> 01:01:35,020
Did you happen to see
a show last August

1215
01:01:35,090 --> 01:01:38,060
that had to do with a man
who was being blackmailed
by a woman?

1216
01:01:38,560 --> 01:01:41,260
Oh, yes, sir,
I did see that show. Yes.

1217
01:01:41,660 --> 01:01:44,290
He shot her.

1218
01:01:46,070 --> 01:01:47,060
Exactly.

1219
01:01:49,070 --> 01:01:52,010
Why would Claire Daley
blackmail Ward Fowler?

1220
01:01:52,770 --> 01:01:54,210
And then how?

1221
01:01:55,840 --> 01:01:57,810
That's where I'm gonna need
your help, Lieutenant.

1222
01:01:58,380 --> 01:01:59,970
Have you, by any chance,

1223
01:02:00,050 --> 01:02:02,140
checked with
the Toronto police by now?

1224
01:02:02,950 --> 01:02:06,150
Yes, yes,
as a matter of fact, I have.

1225
01:02:06,490 --> 01:02:09,650
I thought maybe you had.
And they told you...

1226
01:02:09,830 --> 01:02:12,890
They told me that
Charles Kipling was an alias.

1227
01:02:13,760 --> 01:02:15,020
And that's when
you decided to have

1228
01:02:15,100 --> 01:02:17,160
Ward Fowler's fingerprints
checked with the FBI?

1229
01:02:17,300 --> 01:02:19,390
That is absolutely right, sir.

1230
01:02:19,530 --> 01:02:20,690
You're amazing.

1231
01:02:21,470 --> 01:02:25,800
Yes, it turns out that
Ward Fowler's real name
is not Charles Kipling.

1232
01:02:25,970 --> 01:02:29,380
It's John Snelling
and you're a...

1233
01:02:29,440 --> 01:02:30,780
He's not a Canadian.

1234
01:02:30,850 --> 01:02:32,610
He's an American.

1235
01:02:32,750 --> 01:02:33,910
And he went to Canada

1236
01:02:33,980 --> 01:02:36,970
after he deserted
during the Korean War.

1237
01:02:37,520 --> 01:02:40,040
There you are.
There's your motive.

1238
01:02:41,690 --> 01:02:44,750
How would it look if
America's favorite detective

1239
01:02:44,830 --> 01:02:47,260
were known to be
a Korean War deserter?

1240
01:02:50,030 --> 01:02:51,930
Or hadrt that
occurred to you?

1241
01:02:52,400 --> 01:02:53,830
Oh, yes, sir,
it did occur to me,

1242
01:02:53,900 --> 01:02:56,000
but there's something
wrong with your thinking.

1243
01:02:56,070 --> 01:02:58,060
If you'll forgive
a criticism, sir.

1244
01:02:58,140 --> 01:02:59,470
I look at it this way.

1245
01:02:59,540 --> 01:03:01,510
If Ward Fowler's career
was ruined,

1246
01:03:01,580 --> 01:03:04,100
she wouldn't be able
to blackmail him anymore,
would she?

1247
01:03:04,480 --> 01:03:06,470
He wouldn't have
anymore money.

1248
01:03:06,850 --> 01:03:09,210
And on top of that,
the show would fold.

1249
01:03:09,620 --> 01:03:11,250
And it would be her show.

1250
01:03:12,350 --> 01:03:14,520
Do you understand
my point, sir?

1251
01:03:14,820 --> 01:03:16,480
I mean, does
an intelligent woman

1252
01:03:16,560 --> 01:03:18,750
go and destroy
her only means of income?

1253
01:03:20,560 --> 01:03:22,120
I don't know. Does she?

1254
01:03:22,230 --> 01:03:24,790
It's what that character did
in the show last August.

1255
01:03:25,670 --> 01:03:28,190
That's the implicit threat
of every blackmailer,

1256
01:03:28,270 --> 01:03:30,400
"Pay me or I'll ruin you."

1257
01:03:33,080 --> 01:03:35,840
Can I ask you
a question, sir?

1258
01:03:38,750 --> 01:03:41,180
Why don't we just
ask Ward Fowler

1259
01:03:41,250 --> 01:03:43,480
if he was being blackmailed
or not?

1260
01:03:44,590 --> 01:03:46,180
I asked him.

1261
01:03:46,390 --> 01:03:47,380
And?

1262
01:03:49,220 --> 01:03:51,320
He claims not.

1263
01:03:51,460 --> 01:03:54,660
He claims he has
what he calls a weakness.

1264
01:03:55,330 --> 01:03:59,290
And this weakness
has cost him a great deal

1265
01:03:59,370 --> 01:04:02,340
and Claire Daley
was kind enough
to lend him enough money

1266
01:04:02,400 --> 01:04:04,740
to cover
his rather extensive losses.

1267
01:04:06,240 --> 01:04:08,370
And do you
believe him, sir?

1268
01:04:08,640 --> 01:04:12,080
Taking your argument for him
into account, I think so.

1269
01:04:14,750 --> 01:04:18,280
I'm not sure. Do you?

1270
01:04:19,890 --> 01:04:21,620
Well, it's hard to say,
isn't it?

1271
01:04:21,790 --> 01:04:23,520
I mean,

1272
01:04:23,590 --> 01:04:26,290
taking your argument
against him into account.

1273
01:04:26,660 --> 01:04:28,720
I mean, you know, he had
an awful lot to conceal.

1274
01:04:28,800 --> 01:04:30,460
Did you know that?

1275
01:04:30,570 --> 01:04:35,230
For example, the Army unit
that he deserted from
was the artillery.

1276
01:04:36,740 --> 01:04:38,640
He was an expert marksman.

1277
01:04:39,740 --> 01:04:41,400
I checked on that, too.

1278
01:04:41,640 --> 01:04:43,300
He never told me that.

1279
01:04:43,380 --> 01:04:45,040
You see?

1280
01:04:45,850 --> 01:04:47,820
You never know, do you?

1281
01:04:48,480 --> 01:04:53,180
On the other hand,

1282
01:04:53,920 --> 01:04:55,890
Ward Fowler has an alibi.

1283
01:04:57,690 --> 01:05:00,660
He was with Mark
during the whole time
during the murder.

1284
01:05:02,800 --> 01:05:04,890
And that alibi is ain'tight.

1285
01:05:06,070 --> 01:05:08,300
Is it as ain'tight
as Sid Daley's?

1286
01:05:08,640 --> 01:05:10,730
Oh, I think it's more, sir.

1287
01:05:11,110 --> 01:05:13,340
I mean, a girl
that you're gonna marry

1288
01:05:13,410 --> 01:05:16,070
is much more apt to provide
an alibi than a gofer.

1289
01:05:16,550 --> 01:05:19,640
What do we conclude
from this interrogation?

1290
01:05:20,320 --> 01:05:22,880
Ward Fowler denies
having a motive,

1291
01:05:22,950 --> 01:05:24,890
he won't admit
to having means,

1292
01:05:26,050 --> 01:05:29,220
and he can prove that
he didn't have opportunity.

1293
01:05:30,090 --> 01:05:32,030
So that leaves us
with Sid Daley.

1294
01:05:32,260 --> 01:05:34,250
That's a great third act line,
isn't it?

1295
01:05:35,530 --> 01:05:37,860
"That leaves us
with Sid Daley."

1296
01:05:40,270 --> 01:05:43,530
Well, I think this has been
very helpful, sir.

1297
01:05:44,970 --> 01:05:46,300
Thank you very much.

1298
01:05:46,370 --> 01:05:48,140
I certainly
appreciate it.

1299
01:05:59,320 --> 01:06:01,410
Oh. One more thing, sir.

1300
01:06:01,490 --> 01:06:04,250
We got something else
on the gun.
Did I mention that?

1301
01:06:04,330 --> 01:06:06,160
No, you. Didn't.
What, Lieutenant?

1302
01:06:06,230 --> 01:06:07,660
A thread sir.

1303
01:06:07,730 --> 01:06:08,990
From the parka?

1304
01:06:09,130 --> 01:06:11,400
No, sir.
We haven't traced the garment

1305
01:06:11,470 --> 01:06:13,530
from which
the thread came from yet, sir.

1306
01:06:13,700 --> 01:06:16,070
Lieutenant, if I were you,
I'd get a search warrant

1307
01:06:16,140 --> 01:06:17,470
for all four people involved.

1308
01:06:17,570 --> 01:06:20,270
Yes, sir.
That's just exactly
what I've done, sir.

1309
01:06:20,380 --> 01:06:21,360
In fact...

1310
01:06:21,440 --> 01:06:22,670
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

1311
01:06:34,420 --> 01:06:35,480
Could you
open this, sir?

1312
01:06:35,560 --> 01:06:36,960
I still don't have
the knack.

1313
01:06:42,930 --> 01:06:45,130
I would like for us
to know, Lieutenant,
the meaning of this.

1314
01:06:45,200 --> 01:06:46,220
Sid, please.

1315
01:06:46,330 --> 01:06:49,270
He asked me where you were,
Lieutenant. I hope
it's okay that I told him.

1316
01:06:49,340 --> 01:06:50,900
May I ask
what this was
all about?

1317
01:06:51,310 --> 01:06:52,740
Oh, there's
the sweater.

1318
01:06:52,810 --> 01:06:54,330
Does it match up
with the thread?

1319
01:06:54,410 --> 01:06:55,430
I think so.

1320
01:06:55,510 --> 01:06:57,410
We gotta take it down
to the lab, though,
Lieutenant.

1321
01:06:57,480 --> 01:06:59,640
It's the only
piece of clothing
that even came close.

1322
01:06:59,750 --> 01:07:01,440
I don't know what you're
talking about, Lieutenant,

1323
01:07:01,520 --> 01:07:04,080
but I do know that
suspicion is being
deliberately cast on me

1324
01:07:04,150 --> 01:07:05,350
and I can guess
by whom.

1325
01:07:05,520 --> 01:07:08,110
Well, sir, I won't deny
that Lieutenant Lucerne...

1326
01:07:08,190 --> 01:07:10,520
Will you stop calling him
Lieutenant Lucerne?

1327
01:07:10,590 --> 01:07:12,290
He's a television detective.

1328
01:07:12,430 --> 01:07:15,560
You can't conduct
an investigation
based on his suspicions.

1329
01:07:15,800 --> 01:07:19,160
Well, sir. I did have a reason
beyond his suspicions.

1330
01:07:19,430 --> 01:07:21,400
You see, the gun
that killed your wife, sir,

1331
01:07:21,470 --> 01:07:24,300
had a little piece of thread
that got caught
on the trigger.

1332
01:07:24,470 --> 01:07:27,570
I'm afraid, sir,
that that thread

1333
01:07:27,910 --> 01:07:29,340
came from this sweater.

1334
01:07:29,480 --> 01:07:30,740
A thread from my sweater?

1335
01:07:30,810 --> 01:07:32,540
Yes, sir. Mohair.

1336
01:07:32,610 --> 01:07:34,240
And the lab said
navy blue mohair.

1337
01:07:34,320 --> 01:07:36,340
And I remembered that was
the color of the sweater

1338
01:07:36,420 --> 01:07:38,650
that you were wearing
the first day that I met you.

1339
01:07:38,990 --> 01:07:41,010
The morning
after she was murdered.

1340
01:07:41,220 --> 01:07:42,690
But that's incredible.

1341
01:07:42,760 --> 01:07:44,280
Yes, sir,
I agree with you.

1342
01:07:44,390 --> 01:07:46,190
But I've always had
a good memory for colors.

1343
01:07:46,330 --> 01:07:49,060
Bravo, Lieutenant.
Even I didn't remember that.

1344
01:07:49,200 --> 01:07:50,560
Didrt you, sir?

1345
01:07:50,730 --> 01:07:52,430
My goodness,
that's funny.

1346
01:07:53,240 --> 01:07:54,830
You see,
because one of
the reasons

1347
01:07:54,900 --> 01:07:56,300
that I remembered
the sweater

1348
01:07:56,370 --> 01:07:58,740
was because
you got hooked on it
that day.

1349
01:07:59,110 --> 01:08:01,630
Following
our discussion, sir.

1350
01:08:02,110 --> 01:08:04,370
Supposing Lucerne
was right before

1351
01:08:04,450 --> 01:08:07,010
when he got the idea
that Ward Fowler
was our man.

1352
01:08:07,320 --> 01:08:11,380
Supposing Ward Fowler
had planted that thread
on the gun himself.

1353
01:08:12,090 --> 01:08:13,750
I don't quite follow you.

1354
01:08:13,820 --> 01:08:15,950
Well, sir,
supposing you...

1355
01:08:16,020 --> 01:08:19,550
I mean, supposing
Lieutenant Lucerne
was right,

1356
01:08:20,460 --> 01:08:22,690
and Claire Daley
was blackmailing you

1357
01:08:23,470 --> 01:08:25,330
like in the TV show.

1358
01:08:25,430 --> 01:08:29,300
Lieutenant, I thought
we agreed that I had
what you called

1359
01:08:30,040 --> 01:08:31,800
an iron-clad alibi?

1360
01:08:32,370 --> 01:08:35,280
Ain'tight, sir, that's what
we actually say.

1361
01:08:35,880 --> 01:08:37,940
Yes, sir, but you know
as well as I do

1362
01:08:38,010 --> 01:08:40,350
that you could have
rigged that alibi.

1363
01:08:41,450 --> 01:08:43,140
It was very brave of you, sir,

1364
01:08:43,220 --> 01:08:44,520
to show me
the videotape machine.

1365
01:08:44,590 --> 01:08:46,920
You certainly like
to take a chance.

1366
01:08:48,020 --> 01:08:49,890
And I always wondered,
of course,

1367
01:08:49,960 --> 01:08:53,020
how two drinks could have
given Mark such a hangover.

1368
01:08:53,860 --> 01:08:56,490
I figured it was
phenobarbital.

1369
01:08:57,700 --> 01:08:59,500
And then he would be out.

1370
01:08:59,630 --> 01:09:01,400
And you'd be able
to tape the game,

1371
01:09:01,470 --> 01:09:03,490
and go over to Tony's,
and kill Claire, and get home,

1372
01:09:03,570 --> 01:09:05,060
and then wake up Mark.

1373
01:09:05,440 --> 01:09:09,270
And he would be
disoriented and groggy

1374
01:09:09,340 --> 01:09:11,040
and guilty
about drinking.

1375
01:09:11,110 --> 01:09:13,310
And when you saw
the ballgame on TV,

1376
01:09:13,380 --> 01:09:16,370
and it looked just about
the same as it did
when he passed out,

1377
01:09:16,520 --> 01:09:19,650
he'd be glad to assume
he'd only been out
for a minute or two

1378
01:09:20,290 --> 01:09:23,820
instead of the hour and a half
that had actually passed.

1379
01:09:24,630 --> 01:09:27,030
And you changed his watch,
didn't you?

1380
01:09:27,100 --> 01:09:30,660
And then you changed it back
to the right time
after he was asleep.

1381
01:09:32,070 --> 01:09:34,040
That was a mistake, sir.

1382
01:09:34,640 --> 01:09:37,000
You shouldn't have set it
to the correct time

1383
01:09:37,070 --> 01:09:40,700
because Mark always keeps
his watch five minutes fast.

1384
01:09:40,780 --> 01:09:42,400
I wondered about that.

1385
01:09:42,910 --> 01:09:46,900
A thousand dollar watch
just doesn't lose
five minutes overnight.

1386
01:09:47,020 --> 01:09:48,380
Is that it?

1387
01:09:49,050 --> 01:09:52,920
No, sir. There's
also the height
of the criminal.

1388
01:09:53,290 --> 01:09:55,590
He's about my height.

1389
01:09:56,290 --> 01:09:58,690
And your height

1390
01:09:59,060 --> 01:10:01,050
without the platform shoes.

1391
01:10:02,800 --> 01:10:04,530
And there's
one other thing, sir.

1392
01:10:05,070 --> 01:10:06,830
You're a crack shot.

1393
01:10:06,900 --> 01:10:09,370
Endlessly fascinating,
Lieutenant.

1394
01:10:11,270 --> 01:10:14,140
But as Lieutenant Lucerne
would say,

1395
01:10:14,510 --> 01:10:16,440
"Where there is no proof,
there is no criminal."

1396
01:10:16,510 --> 01:10:18,070
Fascinating,
notwithstanding.

1397
01:10:18,180 --> 01:10:20,670
But I think, sir,
I have the proof.

1398
01:10:20,950 --> 01:10:21,940
Here.

1399
01:10:32,690 --> 01:10:33,680
What proof?

1400
01:10:36,200 --> 01:10:38,390
WARD:
Lieutenant, there are
no fingerprints on that gun.

1401
01:10:38,470 --> 01:10:40,490
You said so yourself
this morning.

1402
01:10:45,610 --> 01:10:48,630
This has been a rather silly
demonstration, Lieutenant.

1403
01:10:50,510 --> 01:10:52,540
Well, you're absolutely right
again, sir.

1404
01:10:52,650 --> 01:10:55,580
The killer cleaned the gun
of all incriminating prints.

1405
01:10:55,650 --> 01:10:59,050
But the thing is,
he forgot something.

1406
01:10:59,250 --> 01:11:00,520
Forgot what?

1407
01:11:00,620 --> 01:11:04,250
Well, sir, you know that
this gun was only
used as a prop.

1408
01:11:04,630 --> 01:11:08,360
So, of course, it was
never filled with
anything but blanks.

1409
01:11:08,630 --> 01:11:11,030
That is,
until you stole it, sir.

1410
01:11:11,170 --> 01:11:12,760
And in order to
kill Mrs. Daley,

1411
01:11:12,830 --> 01:11:16,430
you had to remove the blanks
and insert real bullets.

1412
01:11:17,510 --> 01:11:19,300
There were no prints
on the gun

1413
01:11:19,370 --> 01:11:21,900
because you
wiped the gun clean, sir.

1414
01:11:22,140 --> 01:11:25,770
But there is a reason
that the lab report
took so long.

1415
01:11:25,980 --> 01:11:28,680
You remembered
to clean the gun.

1416
01:11:31,820 --> 01:11:35,450
But you didn't remember
to do the same thing
with the bullets.

1417
01:11:37,890 --> 01:11:38,980
Damn!

1418
01:11:42,100 --> 01:11:44,260
I had to forget something.

1419
01:11:47,000 --> 01:11:49,370
That's always
how the third act ends.

1420
01:11:51,940 --> 01:11:55,100
You see, I've had
no rehearsal as a murderer.

1421
01:11:55,180 --> 01:11:57,200
I'm, after all, a detective.

1422
01:11:58,410 --> 01:12:00,610
Yes, sir, but

1423
01:12:00,680 --> 01:12:03,280
you did kill Claire Daley,
didn't you, sir?

1424
01:12:06,050 --> 01:12:08,610
She was a blackmailer.

1425
01:12:09,690 --> 01:12:12,060
And I killed her.

1426
01:12:12,260 --> 01:12:14,920
And up to now,
I'm glad I killed her.

1427
01:12:16,130 --> 01:12:19,430
And I believe
that in this killing

1428
01:12:21,370 --> 01:12:23,700
the murderer
has the sympathetic part.

1429
01:12:27,410 --> 01:12:29,310
Does that satisfy you?

1430
01:12:29,510 --> 01:12:31,640
Yes, sir.
That satisfies me.

1431
01:12:32,480 --> 01:12:35,310
Lieutenant, you would do me
an enormous favor

1432
01:12:35,520 --> 01:12:37,580
if you stopped calling me sir.

